* cooperate and consult with other public institutions whose powers and functions impact on this Act;
* liaise or interface with similar organs in other countries or international institutions dealing with forestry conservation and management; and
* perform any other functions as are necessary or incidental to the carrying out of its functions under this Act.
* promote a community-based natural resource management approach in respect of forest management;
* facilitate and simplify the licensing system under this Act and collaborate with other regulatory authorities in the administration of the single licensing system;
* encourage cooperation and partnerships with communities and civil society organisations in the implementation of this Act;
* ensure the uniform application of this Act;
* ensure the efficient and effective operation of the Department; and
* conduct any other activity specified under this Act or that is necessary for the implementation of this Act.

The appointment of an honorary forest officer may be•
* general, so that the honorary forest officer is empowered to act in any part of the Republic or in a National Forest, Local Forest or other area specified in the notice of appointment; or
* limited, so that the honorary forest officer is empowered to act in areas of their residence, including any forest, as may be specified in the instrument of appointment.
* the principle that forests and trees shall be managed as an asset for succeeding generations;
* the need to apply the precautionary principle to the development, management, utilisation and conservation of forest ecosystems, biological diversity and habitats, taking into account the best scientific evidence available;
* the development, management, utilisation and conservation of forests and trees to achieve a sound ecological balance;
* the need to achieve optimum utilisation and ecologically sustainable development and management of forest ecosystems, biological diversity and habitats;
* the need to conserve forests and trees as living resources for both present and future generations and to achieve economic growth, human resource development and employment creation;
* the need to protect biological diversity in forest areas and protect the ecosystem as a whole, including species which are not targeted for exploitation;

the implementation of international agreements to which Zambia is party.
