		* the health and vitality of forests;
		* the productive functions of forests;
		* the protective and environmental functions of forests; and
		* the social functions of forests;

(1) A person shall not, in a botanical reserve and without the prior approval of the Director•
* fell, cut or damage any tree or re-generation of the tree or biodiversity in the botanical reserve;
* squat, camp, reside, build or excavate, construct or use any enclosure,  re-open or use any road other than a public road, or erect or operate any plant, machinery or equipment;
* set fire to any tree, undergrowth, grass or forest produce, assist in lighting any fire or allow any fire to be lit by any person or allow any person to enter the botanical reserve;
* graze domestic animals or allow domestic animals to trespass;
* clear, cultivate or break up land for cultivation or other purposes, or grow crops;
* enter or be found in or upon the botanical reserve or for any purpose contrary to an order made by the Director, unless the person is a traveller on a public road;
* collect any bees, honey, comb, or beeswax, or hang or place on any tree or elsewhere any beehive or other receptacle for the purpose of obtaining any bees, comb, honey or beeswax, or be found in, or upon, the botanical reserve for the purpose of collecting any bees, honey, comb, or beeswax;
* remove or damage any boundary mark, beacon, notice, fence or gate, or remove or damage any mark placed on any tree by, or on, the authority of a forest officer; or

The Director shall, in determining whether to approve an application under subsection (1), have regard to•
* the uses to which the applicant is proposing to put the land, the manner in which it will be done and the compatibility of the uses with sustainable forest management;
* the resources available to the applicant and likely to be applied to the land;
* the current use and management of the land;
* the environmental impact assessment undertaken in respect of the land; or
* any comments or representations from the local community in the area who are likely to be affected by the registration of the area as a private forest.
* arrangements for and methods of felling trees, including the rates of extraction of timber on the land;
* in consultation with the relevant regulatory authority, construction of roads, bridges, buildings and other structures on the land;

The terms and conditions referred to in subsection (3) may include•
* arrangements for and methods of transporting timber within and out of the land;
* gathering and utilisation of forest products from the land;
* afforestation and re-forestation of the land;
* in consultation with the Zambia Environmental Management Agency, disposal of waste;
* prevention of pollution;
* conservation of flora and fauna on the land;
* consultation with persons living near the land and deriving some or all of their livelihood from the land;
* cooperation with right holders in respect of existing rights;
* the duration of the registration and the terms of its renewal;
* the payment of rent, fees or royalties in respect of the land;
* rendering of reports to the Department, local authority or local community in the area;
* the settling of any disputes in respect of the land;  and
* such other matters as may be prescribed.
* criterion for registration of private forests;
* procedure for applying for registration, renewal, transfer and cancellation of registration; and
* terms and conditions of registration, renewal, transfer or cancellation of registration.
* technical advice on forest management and conservation; and
* subject to availability of funds, loans from the Fund for the development and management of the private forest.

A community forest management group shall be guided by the following principles:
* persons living in close proximity to or deriving their livelihood from or having strong traditional ties to the forest shall be given an opportunity to join a community forest management group;
* the purposes for which the community forest management group is formed shall be implemented to promote sustainable management of forest ecosystems and biological diversity;
* the purposes for which the community forest management group is formed shall be explained to all persons wishing to join the community forest management group;
* the management of the community forest management group, the management of any funds and the selection of the leaders of the community forest management group shall be based on transparency, fairness, impartiality and non-discrimination;
* members of a community forest management group shall be encouraged to participate in the management of the community  forest management group; and
* the procedures for membership of the community forest management group or guidelines regulating the conduct of members of the community forest management group shall be based on, and conducted in accordance with, the principles of natural justice.
* is recognised within the community which is within or adjacent to a local forest; and
* derives their livelihood from the forest.

(1) A community forest management group that is party to a community forestry agreement for a community forest shall•
* protect, conserve and manage the community forest or part thereof pursuant to the community forestry agreement and the management plan for the community forest;
* formulate and implement forest management consistent with traditional forest user rights of the local community in accordance with sustainable forest management;
* protect sacred groves and protected trees in the community forest;
* assist the Director in enforcing the provisions of this Act in relation to illegal harvesting of forest produce;
* with the approval of the Director, enter into partnerships with otherpersons for the purposes of ensuring the efficient and sustainable conservation and management of the community forest;
* keep the Director informed of any developments, changes and occurrences within the community forest which are critical for the conservation of biodiversity;
* help in fire-fighting within and around the community forest; and
* do any other thing that is necessary for the efficient conservation and management of the community forest.
* collection of medicinal herbs;
* harvesting of honey;
* harvesting of timber or fuel wood;
* grass harvesting and grazing of animals;
* collection of forest produce for community based industries;
* eco-tourism and recreational activities;
* scientific and educational activities;
* plantation establishment through non-resident cultivation;
* the right to enter into contracts to assist in carrying out specified silvicultural operations;

A joint forest management committee shall, not later than one hundred and eighty days after the end of the financial year, submit to the local community and the Director•
* an audited balance sheet;
* an audited statement of income and expenditure; and
* a report concerning its activities during that financial year.
* include such maps and descriptive matter as may be necessary to illustrate the proposals in the management plan;

Orders given under subsection (1) or (2) may relate to• (a) the allocation of the uses of land for arable, pasture, woodland or forest purposes or for water catchment;
* the construction and maintenance of works for conserving water or soil and other works to preserve or improve natural resources;
* the prohibition or restriction of cultivation of any part of the land;
* the method of cultivation of land and the system of farming to be used on the land;
* the manner of watering, managing, pasturing and moving livestock;
* the preservation and protection of the source, course and banks of any stream;
* the control of water, including storm water, drainage water and floods;
* the prevention of pollution or fouling of public water as defined in the Water Resources Management Act, 2011;
* the preservation of trees and other vegetation and the method and systems by which forest produce may be taken and used;
* measures to prevent, control or combat fires, including the making of firebreaks and carrying out control burning; or
* measures to prevent, control or combat fires, including the making of firebreaks and carrying out control burning; or
